From: Parsec Web <patches@parsec.os>
Date: 2026-02-12
Subject: [PATCH 5/5] Add Chrome-compatible APIs at engine level for site compatibility

Adds web APIs that Chrome ships but WebKit doesn't expose by default.
These are the most common causes of real-world site breakage when
running on a non-Chrome engine.

APIs added at the WebCore/IDL level (not just JS shims):

  1. window.scheduler — Task Scheduling API
       Used by React 18+, Vue 3, Angular, SolidJS, and many build tools.
       Without it frameworks fall back to worse scheduling via setTimeout.
       Spec: https://wicg.github.io/scheduling-apis/

  2. navigator.connection — Network Information API
       Used by adaptive loading (Google, Twitter, etc.).
       Without it, sites load full-resolution assets regardless of network.
       Spec: https://wicg.github.io/netinfo/

  3. window.reportingObserver — Reporting API
       Used by analytics and error monitoring. Sites check for existence.
       Spec: https://www.w3.org/TR/reporting/

  4. CSS.highlights — Custom Highlight API
       Used by code editors (VS Code Web, CodeMirror, Monaco).
       Without it, syntax highlighting falls back to DOM-heavy approach.
       Spec: https://drafts.csswg.org/css-highlight-api-1/

  5. navigator.userAgentData — UA Client Hints
       Structured UA parsing. Sites check this before navigator.userAgent.
       Parsec reports as Chrome/131 for maximum site compatibility.

  6. document.hasStorageAccess — Storage Access API
       Required for cross-origin auth flows (OAuth, SSO, embeds).
       Without it, login iframes fail silently on many sites.

